00:36:35.584 --> 00:36:37.250
but it's really
confidence and believing

00:36:37.250 --> 00:36:38.940
in yourself and those things.

00:36:38.940 --> 00:36:41.840
But theres, I think
with all people,

00:36:41.840 --> 00:36:43.740
maybe women
especially in business

00:36:43.740 --> 00:36:46.680
and in the
entrepreneurial world,

00:36:46.680 --> 00:36:48.912
there's a fine
line to walk there.

00:36:48.912 --> 00:36:50.370
LINDA ROTTENBERG:
A great question,

00:36:50.370 --> 00:36:51.920
and I will answer
it in two ways.

00:36:51.920 --> 00:36:57.310
With the Globant
boys, they just seemed

00:36:57.310 --> 00:37:00.110
to have had everything
figured out.

00:37:00.110 --> 00:37:02.110
And we thought would
they even take advice?

00:37:02.110 --> 00:37:04.140
I think that was
the question we had.

00:37:04.140 --> 00:37:05.560
And I'm so proud of them.

00:37:05.560 --> 00:37:07.980
And they say that it's a
defining moment-- there

00:37:07.980 --> 00:37:10.630
were four founders--
they all four met,

00:37:10.630 --> 00:37:12.600
they wept, and then
when they found out

00:37:12.600 --> 00:37:14.070
they were rejected
the first time.

00:37:14.070 --> 00:37:15.350
And they met and
they decided we're

00:37:15.350 --> 00:37:16.980
going to go through
this process again.

00:37:16.980 --> 00:37:18.479
And I will tell
you, in part because

00:37:18.479 --> 00:37:20.590
of that story and the
success they've had,

00:37:20.590 --> 00:37:24.130
but how impactful it was
to actually face rejection

00:37:24.130 --> 00:37:27.720
and have to come back and
change their own approach, now

00:37:27.720 --> 00:37:30.070
20% of the entrepreneurs
Endeavor selects are

00:37:30.070 --> 00:37:34.780
rejected the first time and come
back, which is pretty amazing.

00:37:34.780 --> 00:37:37.560
With regard to women,
so one of the things

00:37:37.560 --> 00:37:40.420
I hear a lot is, well, people
have these connections.

00:37:40.420 --> 00:37:43.150
When you go in Silicon Valley,
there's a sense only 8%

00:37:43.150 --> 00:37:45.440
of female led companies
are venture backed.

00:37:45.440 --> 00:37:47.870
And since we're not part of
the club, and what can we do?

00:37:47.870 --> 00:37:50.760
And what I always
say is that there's

00:37:50.760 --> 00:37:52.642
the dark arts of
entrepreneurship

00:37:52.642 --> 00:37:54.350
that they don't teach
in business school.

00:37:54.350 --> 00:37:56.250
And many people of
all genders use,

00:37:56.250 --> 00:37:59.142
but I found particular
I used and some

00:37:59.142 --> 00:38:00.850
of my favorite female
entrepreneurs used.

00:38:00.850 --> 00:38:04.660
And I'll tell one story,
and it is of stalking.

00:38:04.660 --> 00:38:08.710
Let me say, stalking is an
underrated start-up strategy.

00:38:08.710 --> 00:38:11.240
And I used to trap people
in confined spaces.

00:38:11.240 --> 00:38:15.740
But my favorite story is a woman
named Josephine Esther Mentzer.

00:38:15.740 --> 00:38:20.270
And she grows up in a Hungarian
Jewish family in Queens.

00:38:20.270 --> 00:38:24.380
And she grows up very poor,
but aspires to luxury.

00:38:24.380 --> 00:38:27.335
So she sees a woman at a beauty
salon with this nice blouse

00:38:27.335 --> 00:38:29.130
and says, where did
you get that blouse?

00:38:29.130 --> 00:38:31.850
And the woman looks at her
and says, what does it matter?

00:38:31.850 --> 00:38:33.440
You could never afford it.

00:38:33.440 --> 00:38:38.290
And Estelle, as she's known,
Josephine, she gets so mad

00:38:38.290 --> 00:38:40.090
and she says, I'm
going to have it all.

00:38:40.090 --> 00:38:40.980
I'm going to have the luxury.

00:38:40.980 --> 00:38:42.063
I'm going to have the art.

00:38:42.063 --> 00:38:45.900
And she realizes that her uncle
John is this struggling chemist

00:38:45.900 --> 00:38:47.460
who can't sell these products.

00:38:47.460 --> 00:38:49.210
So she goes and
literally stalks people

00:38:49.210 --> 00:38:52.210
outside of Salvation Army
meetings and in the elevators

00:38:52.210 --> 00:38:54.861
and says that her all purpose
cream can solve their wrinkles.

00:38:54.861 --> 00:38:56.360
They don't think
they have wrinkles,

00:38:56.360 --> 00:38:58.180
but nonetheless she does this.

00:38:58.180 --> 00:38:59.980
And she builds up a
nice little business,

00:38:59.980 --> 00:39:02.330
but she does not want
to sell in drugstores.

00:39:02.330 --> 00:39:03.600
She covets luxury.

00:39:03.600 --> 00:39:05.840
She wants to sell at
Saks Fifth Avenue.

00:39:05.840 --> 00:39:07.790
So she starts
stalking the buyer.

00:39:07.790 --> 00:39:08.860
But he's like, I'm sorry.

00:39:08.860 --> 00:39:10.401
There's this unknown
brand and you're

00:39:10.401 --> 00:39:11.530
this unknown entrepreneur.

00:39:11.530 --> 00:39:12.530
No way.

00:39:12.530 --> 00:39:13.564
And she says, all right.

00:39:13.564 --> 00:39:15.980
I've got to do two things,
I've got to get more strategic.

00:39:15.980 --> 00:39:17.930
So first she changes her name.

00:39:17.930 --> 00:39:19.460
So it was Josephine
Esther Mentzer.

00:39:19.460 --> 00:39:23.780
She changes it to Estee and
takes her married name, Lauder.

00:39:23.780 --> 00:39:27.350
And the next thing she does
is at the Waldorf Astoria,

00:39:27.350 --> 00:39:29.640
there's this charity
luncheon and she gives away

00:39:29.640 --> 00:39:32.110
these lipsticks in these
metallic sheaths, which are

00:39:32.110 --> 00:39:33.920
this big step up from plastic.

00:39:33.920 --> 00:39:35.900
And the women get one
free one and ask her

00:39:35.900 --> 00:39:37.130
where they can buy another.

00:39:37.130 --> 00:39:40.390
And she says, oh, why don't
you try Saks down the street?

00:39:40.390 --> 00:39:42.790
And as the buyer
then says-- there

00:39:42.790 --> 00:39:45.840
was a line that forms
from the Waldorf Astoria

00:39:45.840 --> 00:39:47.460
all the way to
Saks Fifth Avenue.

00:39:47.460 --> 00:39:49.110
And the next day,
he places an order.

00:39:49.110 --> 00:39:51.855
So yes, stalking is
underrated start-up strategy.

00:39:54.639 --> 00:39:55.430
AUDIENCE: Hi Linda.

00:39:55.430 --> 00:39:57.390
Thank you for your talk and
thank you for that story.

00:39:57.390 --> 00:39:59.200
Actually, my team
calls on Estee Lauder

00:39:59.200 --> 00:40:02.860
and we actually want to try
and remind the Estee Lauder

00:40:02.860 --> 00:40:05.700
business to be a little bit
more like the founder today,

00:40:05.700 --> 00:40:06.860
because it's gotten so big.

00:40:06.860 --> 00:40:09.240
So we're like, how can you
be a little bit more nimble

00:40:09.240 --> 00:40:10.240
in today's world?

00:40:10.240 --> 00:40:12.490
LINDA ROTTENBERG: You have
to go back to the founding.

00:40:12.490 --> 00:40:13.470
AUDIENCE: The DNA of--right.

00:40:13.470 --> 00:40:15.386
LINDA ROTTENBERG: In
fact, GE when it came out

00:40:15.386 --> 00:40:18.680
of the financial crisis, they
went back to Thomas Edison

00:40:18.680 --> 00:40:20.640
and said, we're
builders, not bankers.

00:40:20.640 --> 00:40:24.430
Because GE Capital had become
such the face of the company.

00:40:24.430 --> 00:40:26.260
They had to go back to
their founding days.

00:40:26.260 --> 00:40:27.390
AUDIENCE: So it's
like staying true--

00:40:27.390 --> 00:40:28.480
LINDA ROTTENBERG:
Good on you, exactly.

00:40:28.480 --> 00:40:30.662
AUDIENCE: --to who you are
throughout the process.

00:40:30.662 --> 00:40:33.432
A question about your
management style.

00:40:33.432 --> 00:40:35.390
So the example you just
gave about your husband

00:40:35.390 --> 00:40:37.590
when he was sick--
and thank goodness

00:40:37.590 --> 00:40:40.700
that everything's great there.

00:40:40.700 --> 00:40:42.410
That was clearly
a moment where you

00:40:42.410 --> 00:40:44.840
had to say, OK, what's
super important to me,

00:40:44.840 --> 00:40:48.320
and probably turn over the reins
of the business to other people

00:40:48.320 --> 00:40:50.050
you trust.

00:40:50.050 --> 00:40:53.090
What are other moments
in your experience

00:40:53.090 --> 00:40:54.990
maybe after that in
the last six years

00:40:54.990 --> 00:40:59.570
that you've had to also say not
just for significant moments,

00:40:59.570 --> 00:41:01.360
but just in the
day to day to help

00:41:01.360 --> 00:41:03.800
other leaders within your
organization stand up

00:41:03.800 --> 00:41:05.742
and find their own voice
and their own ground?

00:41:05.742 --> 00:41:06.700
LINDA ROTTENBERG: Yeah.

00:41:06.700 --> 00:41:10.910
it's partly about giving
people a space to grow,

00:41:10.910 --> 00:41:13.260
and partly knowing your own
strengths and weaknesses

00:41:13.260 --> 00:41:15.970
and realizing that not everyone
is motivated like you are.

00:41:15.970 --> 00:41:18.680
So I'm someone who-- I
don't care about titles.

00:41:18.680 --> 00:41:20.244
I don't care about
vacation days.

00:41:20.244 --> 00:41:22.410
I'm like, you get your work
done, it doesn't matter.

00:41:22.410 --> 00:41:24.964
And I realized after a while,
it actually mattered to people.

00:41:24.964 --> 00:41:26.380
There are people
who wanted rules.

00:41:26.380 --> 00:41:27.550
I was like, you want rules?

00:41:27.550 --> 00:41:28.890
Rules are meant to be broken.

00:41:28.890 --> 00:41:30.320
But no, they wanted rules.

00:41:30.320 --> 00:41:33.820
And our president,
Fernando Fabre--

00:41:33.820 --> 00:41:36.320
I was very unsuccessful
in getting a COO

00:41:36.320 --> 00:41:39.360
because I recruited
from Nike and Disney,

00:41:39.360 --> 00:41:41.490
and I thought people wanted
more corporate people.

00:41:41.490 --> 00:41:43.030
And it turns out
they wanted someone

00:41:43.030 --> 00:41:45.140
who had the DNA of Endeavor.

00:41:45.140 --> 00:41:46.867
And I ended up hiring
three years ago,

00:41:46.867 --> 00:41:48.450
three and a half
years ago, the person

00:41:48.450 --> 00:41:51.010
who is now our president,
Fernando Fabre, who

00:41:51.010 --> 00:41:54.160
had been seven years our
managing director in Mexico.

00:41:54.160 --> 00:41:56.160
And I noted that any
time anyone in the world

00:41:56.160 --> 00:41:57.410
had a problem with
me, they went to him.

00:41:57.410 --> 00:41:57.890
I was like, all right.

00:41:57.890 --> 00:42:00.015
Let's just make this
official and why don't you

00:42:00.015 --> 00:42:00.681
come be the COO.

00:42:00.681 --> 00:42:02.990
He was like, I'm not
doing that failed title

00:42:02.990 --> 00:42:04.930
with these two failed COOs.

00:42:04.930 --> 00:42:06.820
You make me president,
and I'll move.

00:42:06.820 --> 00:42:11.300
So el presidente
now sets the agenda.

00:42:11.300 --> 00:42:15.907
And it's been so nice, and we
respect each other so well.

00:42:15.907 --> 00:42:17.490
But having those
complementary skills,

00:42:17.490 --> 00:42:22.090
there are some people who
really need the structure

00:42:22.090 --> 00:42:22.860
that he wants.

00:42:22.860 --> 00:42:24.320
There's some people
want-- and I'm

00:42:24.320 --> 00:42:27.800
freed up to give the
love and the inspiration.

00:42:27.800 --> 00:42:33.030
And I think it goes back to
knowing yourself and realizing

00:42:33.030 --> 00:42:36.340
to get going, it's all
about you and your idea.

00:42:36.340 --> 00:42:38.950
But to go big, it's
about co-creation.

00:42:38.950 --> 00:42:41.070
And to go big, if it
remains all about you,

00:42:41.070 --> 00:42:44.340
you're not getting very far.

00:42:44.340 --> 00:42:45.970
AUDIENCE: So that
actually set me

00:42:45.970 --> 00:42:48.220
up perfectly for the question
that I was going to ask.

00:42:48.220 --> 00:42:52.780
Which is you do a brilliant
job demystifying that there

00:42:52.780 --> 00:42:57.700
is a single archetype
of an entrepreneur,

00:42:57.700 --> 00:43:01.260
and really breaking it down into
the different flavors of that.

00:43:01.260 --> 00:43:06.280
And I think probably one of
the things that I experience

00:43:06.280 --> 00:43:09.320
and I see talked about
and in talking to people

00:43:09.320 --> 00:43:17.510
is it's a very sort
of solo archetype,

00:43:17.510 --> 00:43:19.890
the original entrepreneur
is, that I'm doing it myself.

00:43:19.890 --> 00:43:20.530
It's my idea.

00:43:20.530 --> 00:43:22.590
I'm creating it on my own.

00:43:22.590 --> 00:43:26.119
But you mentioned the concept
of surrounding yourself

00:43:26.119 --> 00:43:28.660
with the right people that will
complement your skills, which

00:43:28.660 --> 00:43:30.204
I think is really important.

00:43:30.204 --> 00:43:31.620
And especially at
Google, we're so

00:43:31.620 --> 00:43:34.860
fortunate to work amongst
brilliant, talented

00:43:34.860 --> 00:43:36.030
individuals.

00:43:36.030 --> 00:43:39.740
So I'm curious to get your
take on your own companies,

00:43:39.740 --> 00:43:42.090
the Endeavor companies.

00:43:42.090 --> 00:43:45.260
Have you experienced
people coming in

00:43:45.260 --> 00:43:49.280
and, for lack of a better
word, hoarding the idea

00:43:49.280 --> 00:43:51.929
and you sending them back and
saying listen, great idea,

00:43:51.929 --> 00:43:54.470
but go surround yourself with
people who could make it happen

00:43:54.470 --> 00:43:56.720
or to refine it.

00:43:56.720 --> 00:43:57.820
LINDA ROTTENBERG: Yeah.

00:43:57.820 --> 00:44:00.340
Entrepreneurship is
not a solo sport.

00:44:00.340 --> 00:44:02.950
And I think not only
are there studies

00:44:02.950 --> 00:44:04.930
that many of the most
successful companies

00:44:04.930 --> 00:44:09.590
are run by pairs or trios
of founders, not just one.

00:44:09.590 --> 00:44:11.950
I should say also the
two fastest growing group

00:44:11.950 --> 00:44:15.490
starting businesses today
are baby boomers over 55

00:44:15.490 --> 00:44:17.640
and actually women
are now starting

00:44:17.640 --> 00:44:21.529
to launch companies at faster
rates than ever before.

00:44:21.529 --> 00:44:23.570
So back to you don't need
to be a boy in a hoodie

00:44:23.570 --> 00:44:26.030
to be an entrepreneur.

00:44:26.030 --> 00:44:28.700
Here's the thing I will
end on because it's

00:44:28.700 --> 00:44:31.450
so emblematic of what I've
learned at Endeavor, which

00:44:31.450 --> 00:44:34.800
is not only in companies do
you need to surround yourself

00:44:34.800 --> 00:44:38.010
with this group of people
that are the co-creators,

00:44:38.010 --> 00:44:40.050
not only do you
need not just one

00:44:40.050 --> 00:44:43.471
mentor, but a circle of
mentors, but the process

00:44:43.471 --> 00:44:44.970
of entrepreneurship
itself, Endeavor

00:44:44.970 --> 00:44:47.990
is now looking at
what makes cities

00:44:47.990 --> 00:44:49.760
conducive to entrepreneurship.

00:44:49.760 --> 00:44:53.590
And it is not top down
regulatory changes.

00:44:53.590 --> 00:44:55.340
it is not creating incubators.

00:44:55.340 --> 00:44:56.860
It is not creating VC firms.

00:44:56.860 --> 00:45:01.880
It is successful entrepreneurs
mentoring, investing in,

00:45:01.880 --> 00:45:04.090
and inspiring the
next generation.

00:45:04.090 --> 00:45:09.070
So what we've done in Argentina,
in Istanbul, in Amman, Jordan,

00:45:09.070 --> 00:45:12.590
now we just released yesterday
a tech map of New York,

00:45:12.590 --> 00:45:16.090
are what happens when successful
entrepreneurs pay it froward.

00:45:16.090 --> 00:45:19.430
And, in fact, you see
this incredible effect

00:45:19.430 --> 00:45:23.160
of them going and angel
investing and mentoring.

00:45:23.160 --> 00:45:25.090
And that's how
entrepreneurship breeds.

00:45:25.090 --> 00:45:26.548
So one of the things
we're doing is

00:45:26.548 --> 00:45:28.880
saying this is happening
very well in many places,

00:45:28.880 --> 00:45:31.200
but mainly in tech and
mainly with the guys.

00:45:31.200 --> 00:45:34.840
So back to the women question,
back to the non-tech question.

00:45:34.840 --> 00:45:36.550
We're saying if
you're in retail,

00:45:36.550 --> 00:45:39.990
if you're in food and beverage,
if you're women, if you're

00:45:39.990 --> 00:45:41.050
an older person, do this.

00:45:41.050 --> 00:45:41.550
Give back.

00:45:41.550 --> 00:45:44.800
Spend part of your time
mentoring and angel investing,

00:45:44.800 --> 00:45:48.030
because that's actually
the way that an ecosystem,

00:45:48.030 --> 00:45:52.220
that a community of
entrepreneurs is created.

00:45:52.220 --> 00:45:52.930
Thank you.

00:45:52.930 --> 00:45:54.180
Thank you all.

00:45:54.180 --> 00:45:55.730
[APPLAUSE]

